# Git configuration and sync (GitLab.com / GitHub.com)

## Git configuration by remote

Always set git configuration according to the destination remote when pushing branches:

- **When pushing to GitLab.com** (remote `gitlab` or host `gitlab.com`):  
  Use identity **sweeden3**.
  ```bash
  git config user.name "sweeden3"
  git config user.email "sweeden3@gitlab"   # or your GitLab-associated email
  ```
  Apply before push: `git push gitlab <branch>`.

- **When pushing to GitHub.com** (remote `origin` or host `github.com`):  
  Use identity **sweeden-ttu**.
  ```bash
  git config user.name "sweeden-ttu"
  git config user.email "sweeden-ttu@github"   # or your GitHub-associated email
  ```
  Apply before push: `git push origin <branch>`.

If you use a single working tree for both remotes, switch config per push, or use per-remote config (e.g. `git config --global user.name` for the default and override per-repo when switching remotes).

